<div class="container-fluid main-container">




<div class="fluid-row" id="header">



<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Intro to R workshop</h1>
<h4 class="author">Albina Gibadullina and Maria Laricheva</h4>
<h4 class="date">September 24, 2021</h4>

</div>


<div id="intro-to-r-and-rstudio" class="section level1">
<h1>Intro to R and RStudio</h1>
<div id="installing-and-loading-needed-packages" class="section level2">
<h2>Installing and loading needed packages</h2>
<p>Install R packages</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#install.packages(&quot;tidyverse&quot;)
#install.packages(&quot;gapminder&quot;)</code></pre>
<p>Load R packages</p>
<pre class="r"><code>library(tidyverse) # a collection of R packages designed for data science (e.g.dplyr, ggplot2, tidyr, forcats)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## -- Attaching packages --------------------------------------- tidyverse 1.3.0 --</code></pre>
<pre><code>## v ggplot2 3.3.5     v purrr   0.3.4
## v tibble  3.1.4     v dplyr   1.0.7
## v tidyr   1.1.3     v stringr 1.4.0
## v readr   2.0.1     v forcats 0.5.1</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.0.5</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: package 'tibble' was built under R version 4.0.5</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: package 'tidyr' was built under R version 4.0.5</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: package 'readr' was built under R version 4.0.5</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: package 'dplyr' was built under R version 4.0.5</code></pre>
<pre><code>## -- Conflicts ------------------------------------------ tidyverse_conflicts() --
## x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>library(gapminder) # a package with the gapminder dataset</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="manually-inputting-andor-modifying-values" class="section level2">
<h2>Manually inputting and/or modifying values</h2>
<div id="creating-new-variables" class="section level3">
<h3>Creating new variables</h3>
<p>Assign values to variables</p>
<pre class="r"><code>a &lt;- 4
a</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 4</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>b &lt;- 5
b</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 5</code></pre>
<p>Create a new variable from existing variables</p>
<pre class="r"><code>c &lt;- 6+a
c</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 10</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>d &lt;- a + b + c
d</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 19</code></pre>
<p>See if two variables equal to one another</p>
<pre class="r"><code>c==d</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] FALSE</code></pre>
<p>See if two variables are not equal to one another</p>
<pre class="r"><code>c!=d</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="working-with-vectors" class="section level3">
<h3>Working with vectors</h3>
<p>Create a vector</p>
<pre class="r"><code>vec &lt;- c(0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
vec</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 0 1 2 3 4 5</code></pre>
<p>Select the first value of vec:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>vec[1]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 0</code></pre>
<p>And here is how you can modify it:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>vec[1] &lt;- 1000
vec</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1000    1    2    3    4    5</code></pre>
<p>You can replace multiple values at once as long as the number of new values equals the number of selected values:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>vec[c(1, 3, 5)] &lt;- c(-1, -2, -3)
vec</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] -1  1 -2  3 -3  5</code></pre>
<p>Add +1 to column 4 to 6</p>
<pre class="r"><code>vec[4:6] &lt;- vec[4:6] + 1
vec</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] -1  1 -2  4 -2  6</code></pre>
<p>You can also create values that do not yet exist in your object. R will expand the object to accommodate the new values:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>vec[7] &lt;- 10
vec</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] -1  1 -2  4 -2  6 10</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="working-with-data-frames" class="section level1">
<h1>Working with data frames</h1>
<p>Create a data frame with four variables</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df &lt;- data.frame(c(&quot;Anna&quot;,&quot;Patrick&quot;,&quot;John&quot;),c(165,170,168),c(18000,45000,57000),c(&quot;youth&quot;,&quot;senior&quot;,&quot;adult&quot;))
names(df) &lt;- c(&quot;Name&quot;,&quot;Height&quot;, &quot;Income&quot;, &quot;Age&quot;)
df</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      Name Height Income    Age
## 1    Anna    165  18000  youth
## 2 Patrick    170  45000 senior
## 3    John    168  57000  adult</code></pre>
<p>Extract all rows, all colums</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df[,]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      Name Height Income    Age
## 1    Anna    165  18000  youth
## 2 Patrick    170  45000 senior
## 3    John    168  57000  adult</code></pre>
<p>Extract first row and all columns</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df[1,]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   Name Height Income   Age
## 1 Anna    165  18000 youth</code></pre>
<p>Extract first two rows and all columns</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df[1:2,]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      Name Height Income    Age
## 1    Anna    165  18000  youth
## 2 Patrick    170  45000 senior</code></pre>
<p>Extract first and third row and all columns</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df[c(1,3),]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   Name Height Income   Age
## 1 Anna    165  18000 youth
## 3 John    168  57000 adult</code></pre>
<p>Extract first row and second and third column</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df[1,2:3]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   Height Income
## 1    165  18000</code></pre>
<div id="exercise-1" class="section level2">
<h2>Exercise #1:</h2>
<p>Extract third column with all rows</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df[,3]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 18000 45000 57000</code></pre>
<p>Extract element at 2nd row, 3rd column</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df[2,3]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 45000</code></pre>
<p>Substitute element at 2nd row, 3rd column with 50000</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df[2,3] &lt;- 50000
df[2,3]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 50000</code></pre>
<p>You can also extract values using variable names by adding <code>$</code> and variable name after the dataset name</p>
<p>E.g. Extract the first two observations of the <code>Age</code> variable</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df$Age[1:2]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;youth&quot;  &quot;senior&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="changing-format-of-variables" class="section level2">
<h2>Changing format of variables</h2>
<p>Main data types:</p>
<ul>
<li>character (text/strings)</li>
<li>factor (categorical variable)</li>
<li>numeric (quantitative variable)</li>
<li>integer (quantitative variable, only integers)</li>
<li>logical (TRUE or FALSE variable)</li>
</ul>
<p>Check current data format of the <code>Age</code> variable</p>
<pre class="r"><code>class(df$Age)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;character&quot;</code></pre>
<p>Change the format of <code>Age</code> from charachter to factor (categorical)</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df$Age &lt;- as.factor(df$Age)</code></pre>
<p>Check whether <code>Age</code> has factor format</p>
<pre class="r"><code>is.factor(df$Age)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
<p>Check levels for <code>Age</code></p>
<pre class="r"><code>levels(df$Age)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;adult&quot;  &quot;senior&quot; &quot;youth&quot;</code></pre>
<p>If you wanted to re-arrange the order of levels: &quot;youth&quot;, &quot;adult&quot;, &quot;senior&quot;</p>
<pre class="r"><code>df$Age &lt;- fct_relevel(df$Age, c(&quot;youth&quot;, &quot;adult&quot;, &quot;senior&quot;))
#Check levels for `gender`
levels(df$Age)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;youth&quot;  &quot;adult&quot;  &quot;senior&quot;</code></pre>
<div id="commands-to-change-data-type" class="section level4">
<h4>Commands to change data type:</h4>
<ul>
<li>as.numeric (quantitative, continious format)</li>
<li>as.integer (quantitative, discrete format)</li>
<li>as.charachter (text format)</li>
<li>as.factor (categorical format)</li>
<li>as.logical (logical format: TRUE/FALSE)</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="commands-to-check-whether-your-data-type-is-the-following" class="section level4">
<h4>Commands to check whether your data type is the following:</h4>
<ul>
<li>is.numeric (quantitative, continious format)</li>
<li>is.integer (quantitative, discrete format)</li>
<li>is.charachter (text format)</li>
<li>is.factor (categorical format)</li>
<li>is.logical (logical format: TRUE/FALSE)</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>

<pre><code>## # A tibble: 1,704 x 6
##    country     continent  year lifeExp population gdpPercap
##    &lt;fct&gt;       &lt;fct&gt;     &lt;int&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;      &lt;int&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;

<div id="summarise-function" class="section level3">
<h3>Summarise function</h3>
<p>Available sub-functions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Center: mean(), median()</li>
<li>Spread: sd(), IQR(), mad()</li>
<li>Range: min(), max(), quantile()</li>
<li>Position: first(), last(), nth(),</li>
<li>Count: n(), n_distinct()</li>
<li>Logical: any(), all()</li>
</ul>
<p>Find average value of the lifeExp variable</p>
<pre class="r"><code>summarise(countries, mean_lifeExp=mean(lifeExp))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   mean_lifeExp
##          &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1         59.5</code></pre>
<p>Find range of the lifeExp variable</p>
<pre class="r"><code>summarise(countries, range_lifeExp=max(lifeExp)-min(lifeExp))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   range_lifeExp
##           &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1          59.0</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="piping-with-multiple-functions" class="section level2">
<h2>Piping with Multiple Functions</h2>
<p>What if you want to perform multiple functions in R? Use Pipe operator (%&gt;%) in the dplyr package. It allows you to perform multiple functions without using nested parentheses.</p>
<p>This is how piping looks like:</p>
<pre class="r"><code># DataFrame%&gt;%
    #function to execute first %&gt;%
        #function to execute second %&gt;%
            #function to execute third</code></pre>
<div id="group_by-function" class="section level3">
<h3>Group_by function</h3>
<p>Group_by function allows you to do operations by groups. E.g. find maximum life expectancy by continent</p>
<pre class="r"><code>countries %&gt;% 
  group_by(continent) %&gt;% 
  summarise(max_lifeExp=max(lifeExp))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   continent max_lifeExp
##   &lt;fct&gt;           &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 Africa           76.4
## 2 Americas         80.7
## 3 Asia             82.6
## 4 Europe           81.8
## 5 Oceania          81.2</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="example-of-piping" class="section level3">
<h3>Example of Piping:</h3>
<p>Finding average life expectancy in each continent in 2007</p>
<ul>
<li>Select country, continent, year, lifeExp</li>
<li>Filter observations from 2007</li>
<li>Split data by continents</li>
<li>Summarise the mean life expectancy within each continent</li>
<li>Round the average life expectancy to 2 decimal points</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>countries %&gt;%
  select(country, continent, year, lifeExp) %&gt;% #select country, continent,  year, lifeExp
    filter(year==2007) %&gt;% #filter observations from 2007
      group_by(continent) %&gt;% # split data by continents
          summarise(mean_lifeExp=mean(lifeExp)) %&gt;% #summarise the mean life expectancy within each continent
            mutate(mean_lifeExp=round(mean_lifeExp,2)) # Use mutate to modify existing variable, round mean weight to 2 decimal points</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   continent mean_lifeExp
##   &lt;fct&gt;            &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 Africa            54.8
## 2 Americas          73.6
## 3 Asia              70.7
## 4 Europe            77.6
## 5 Oceania           80.7</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="exercise-2" class="section level3">
<h3>Exercise #2:</h3>
<p>Finding the average of GDP per Capita of Europen countries</p>
<ul>
<li>Filter observations of European countries</li>
<li>Group by year</li>
<li>Summarize the mean gdpPercap</li>
<li>Save the new data frame as <code>gdp_Europe</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Answers:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>gdp_Europe &lt;- countries %&gt;%
  filter(continent==&quot;Europe&quot;) %&gt;%
      group_by(year) %&gt;%
      summarise(mean_gdpPercap=mean(gdpPercap))
gdp_Europe</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 12 x 2
##     year mean_gdpPercap
##    &lt;int&gt;          &lt;dbl&gt;
##  1  1952          5661.
##  2  1957          6963.
##  3  1962          8365.
##  4  1967         10144.
##  5  1972         12480.
##  6  1977         14284.
##  7  1982         15618.
##  8  1987         17214.
##  9  1992         17062.
## 10  1997         19077.
## 11  2002         21712.
## 12  2007         25054.</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="combine-data-sets" class="section level2">
<h2>Combine data sets</h2>
<pre class="r"><code>df1 &lt;- data.frame(ID = 1:3,                      # Create first example data frame
                  X1 = c(&quot;a1&quot;, &quot;a2&quot;,&quot;a3&quot;),
                  stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
df2 &lt;- data.frame(ID = 2:4,                      # Create second example data frame
                  X2 = c(&quot;b1&quot;, &quot;b2&quot;,&quot;b3&quot;),
                  stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
df1</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   ID X1
## 1  1 a1
## 2  2 a2
## 3  3 a3</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>df2</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   ID X2
## 1  2 b1
## 2  3 b2
## 3  4 b3</code></pre>
<p>Left_join: join matching rows from df2 to df1.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>left_join(df1, df2, by = &quot;ID&quot;)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   ID X1   X2
## 1  1 a1 &lt;NA&gt;
## 2  2 a2   b1
## 3  3 a3   b2</code></pre>
<p>Right_join: join matching rows from df1 to df2</p>
<pre class="r"><code>right_join(df1, df2, by = &quot;ID&quot;)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   ID   X1 X2
## 1  2   a2 b1
## 2  3   a3 b2
## 3  4 &lt;NA&gt; b3</code></pre>
<p>Inner_join: retain only rows in both sets</p>
<pre class="r"><code>inner_join(df1, df2, by = &quot;ID&quot;)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   ID X1 X2
## 1  2 a2 b1
## 2  3 a3 b2</code></pre>
<p>Full_join: retain all values, all rows</p>
<pre class="r"><code>full_join(df1, df2, by = &quot;ID&quot;)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   ID   X1   X2
## 1  1   a1 &lt;NA&gt;
## 2  2   a2   b1
## 3  3   a3   b2
## 4  4 &lt;NA&gt;   b3</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="working-with-missing-data" class="section level2">
<h2>Working with missing data</h2>
<div id="missing-values" class="section level3">
<h3>Missing values</h3>
<p>NA denotes missing values: is.na() is used to test objects if they are NA</p>
<pre class="r"><code>x &lt;- c(1, 2, NA, 5, 3)
is.na(x)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="removing-na-values" class="section level3">
<h3>Removing NA Values</h3>
<p>A common task is to remove missing values (NAs)</p>
<pre class="r"><code>x &lt;- c(1, 2, NA, 4, NA, 5)</code></pre>
<p>Exclude vector with all the missing values</p>
<pre class="r"><code>x[!is.na(x)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1 2 4 5</code></pre>
<p>If you want to filter out all the missing values for a given variable from a df</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#df %&gt;% 
  #filter(!is.na(variable))</code></pre>
<p>Example of excluding missing values in a df</p>
<pre class="r"><code># Create a df with missing values from a previous example
df &lt;- full_join(df1, df2, by = &quot;ID&quot;)

# Exclude observations when X1 is NA
df %&gt;% 
  filter(!is.na(X1))</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   ID X1   X2
## 1  1 a1 &lt;NA&gt;
## 2  2 a2   b1
## 3  3 a3   b2</code></pre>
<p>What if there are multiple things and you want to take the subset with no missing values?</p>
<pre class="r"><code>x &lt;- c(1, 2, NA, 4, NA, 5)
y &lt;- c(&quot;a&quot;, NA, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;d&quot;, NA, &quot;f&quot;)</code></pre>
<p>Leave values that are not missing for both x and y</p>
<pre class="r"><code>good &lt;- complete.cases(x, y)
x[good]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1 4 5</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>y[good]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;a&quot; &quot;d&quot; &quot;f&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
